sec.p:
Interocular, labral, labial, and total dorsal and dorsolateral abd.II–III–IV chaetotaxy are specially useful characters. The number of setae on trochanteral organ and manubrial plate is variable according to the size of the specimen, but the maximum number present in specimens of larger size of each species is really informative. Although the color pattern is difficult to use as a diagnostic character in the European Lepidocyrtus species (
Mateos 2008 a
), when it is accompanied by other chaetotaxic and morphological characters it is very useful for specific differentiation. This is the case of L. juliae sp. nov. , which can be clearly distinguished from the other two Greek species by its characteristic color pattern. However, pigmented and unpigmented specimens of L. barbulus sp. nov. have no morphological nor chaetotaxic differences, so they have been considered chromatic forms of the same species.
